My submission for @renderweekly Season 7 Week 2 topic, #rwgoggs

For the uninitiated who are wondering where the cars are at, don't worry, they'll be back.

RenderWeekly is a community for industrial designers. Each season has a number of weeks, where a prompt is given (in this case, goggles) and folks can exercise their design and rendering skills. There are no winners or loosers, just bragging rights if they share your design.

So, these goggles are an original design. The Creamcar branding is also original although influenced in all the right places. You may remember it from my NFT excursion.

This was about 4 hours from the point I scribbled a basic sketch to when I hit "go" on the rendering queue. Modeled using Creo, rendered in Keyshot 10. Hope you can dig it.

A reprise. From @000magazine issue 008 Build, the 991 911 GT3 Targa. Winter 2019

I wanted to revisit this one, one of my favorites, with a couple of twists. The color, now Smyrna Green. Seats, now with a studio cloth -esque athletic fabric. 

New tire models were needed, and I modeled the roll bar instead of editing out the original targa bar seams in post. I would have liked to remodel the entire rear "soft" window, but that might be a project for a different day. 

To get the scoop on the original, dust off issue 008 and have a read. Or pick one up from 000, they still have some copies.

I hope you all dig it.

Hope you all dig the BTS hyperlapse from last night. To answer a few common questions...

-I use Keyshot for rendering and layout.
-I create the graphic elements in SVG using Inkscape.
-There's no rules when designing art cars for myself, I live off happy accidents. 
-98% of the time my models are a mix of scratch-built CAD and purchased/downloaded assets. So I don't sell models typically. I have a few wheels, tires, and bikes on Gumroad that are 100% my own to sell.
